fields.descriptive_line:
[Leather panel] Gilt leather panel with the pattern of a diaper of ogee-shaped compartments, each containing a 'fleurs-de-lys' device. The pattern has been painted with dark outlines on a gilded ground, which have been punched with several different stamps. The flowers are painted in red, Spanish or Italian, ca. 1500-1600.

fields.physical_description:
[Leather panel] Gilt leather panel with the pattern of a diaper of ogee-shaped compartments, each containing a 'fleurs-de-lys' device. The pattern has been painted with dark outlines on a gilded ground, which have been punched with several different stamps. The flowers are painted in red. This panel was part of a large hanging, described originally as: Gilt leather wall hanging of eight panels with ten horizontal borders and four vertical borders. The pattern consists of a diaper of ogee-shaped compartments, each containing a 'fleurs-de-lys' device. The borders on the sides are decorated with large vases resting resp. on one enriched column and on two columns. The borders at the top and the bottom have floral designs separated by scrolling bands.

fields.history_note:
Purchase price of £180 for a group of leather objects (museum numbers: 821-1898 to 826-1898).
[Leather panel] The pattern of the panels is a very traditional one, of which several different versions are known to exist, amongst other places in the Museum of Leathercraft, Northampton, inventory number 1192-1964; V&A, museum numbers 691-1890, 713-1890; Museo des Artes Decorativos, Madrid, inventory number 291; Museo Episcopal, Vic, inventory number 6251; Museo de la Piel, Igualada, inventory number 843; Deutsches Ledermuseum, Offenbach am Main, inventory number 7701; Schloss Köpenick, Berlin, inventory number 1987.83; Museo Civico, Venice, inventory number unknown; Museo Stibbert, Florence, inventory number 88; Museo Bardini, Florence, inventory number 858.
